cardRatings: 2.9: Laelia, the Blade Reforged

1.8: Osgir, the Reconstructor
2.2: Fain, the Broker
1.5: Audacious Reshapers
3: Laelia, the Blade Reforged
1.8: Ruin Grinder
2.6: Triplicate Titan
additionalComments:
Better than the main set. I've decided to include the whole theme of the Lorehold deck into my cube, including the face commander, as a way to reinvent and rejuvenate the Boros section in my cube (I'll also be making other changes as well). Other than that, Fain, the Broker is like a black Retrofitter Foundry that always has a good mode available, but suffers from being a black 3-drop. I expect Laelia to become a staple through the years to come, I believe she's literally better than Rabblemaster (she *draws cards!!!*). Ruin Grinder is kinda overlooked as a Welder deck target, and even I had a hard time evaluating it in any way. But the fact it bins itself, has evasion, and has a relevant death trigger (even if that death trigger seemingly allows your opponent to benefit from it too) really puts it into the viable category.

There are some cards I won't be testing for other reasons. Archaeomancer's Map just doesn't fit my design goals, but can be very good in land-based ramp environments. The shuffling isn't flavor text either. Paradox Zone is probably the second-best card for cube in terms of raw power level for the entire set, but just seems boring and uninteractive to me.

additionalComments:
Not a ton in commander 2021 that interested me for my cube. There were quite a few "Close" cards, but most just didn't have the power level to make it.
Fain is an interesting value engine that probably isn't strong enough, but is a very interesting card that offers a lot of choice, which is fun.
Laelia is just a super powerful red card that fits in aggressive and midrange decks and has synergy with other random cards. All in all a slam dunk of a card.

2.9: Pest Infestation
2.6: Triplicate Titan
additionalComments: We're already testing 8 cards from Strixhaven, so we decided to avoid borderline cards and rely on others playtesting. At our cube size of 720+, Triplicate Titan is welcome redundancy for every cheat archetype: it's great in the sneak archetype, reanimator, artifact reanimator, tinker, oath, etc. Pest Infestation has enough going for it that it will probably become a permanent fixture of the cube. It works in the token archetype without requiring targets and offering a great rate; the tokens help midrange stabilize with life gain and chump blockers; it works as a 3-for-1 plus at 5 mana, which is awesome. I don't think that cutting rec sage for this is correct since blink, pod, and rec nightmare decks will still prefer sage, but we're always looking to increase the amount of A/E hate, keeping the older unfair A/Es in check (stax artifacts, opposition, sneak, animate dead, oath, swords, etc.)
